What is the difference between an Interface and Abstract class?
A. 1.An interface in java is a contract and has method without implementation and any class which implements this interface
must provide the implementation of those abstract methods. Abstruct class can have both methods with implemention and without implementation
. If an abstract clas has an abstract method , any class extends that abstruct must implements that method.

 2. Methods in interface are public by defaul and fields are final . An abstruct class has fields and method like a normal class and can have
 any access modifier.

  3. We cannot instantiate an interface since it does not have implemented method but we can have instance variable of an interface type that refers
  to an ooject of the class its been implemented by, whereas we can instantiate an abstract class but if that class has an unimplemented
  method, that method must be implemented at the time of instantiation.

Can you make an Object from an Interface and Abstract class ? if not how do you use it ?
A.  We cannot instantiate an interface since it does not have implemented method but we can have instance variable of an interface type that refers
     to an ooject of the class its been implemented by, whereas we can instantiate an abstract class but if that class has an unimplemented
     method, that method must be implemented at the time of instantiation.

what is Access Specifier?
A. Access modifiers of a java class, subclass , interface , field , method , specify who can access them. There are four access modifiers
used in java. They are public, private, protected, no modifier (declaring without an access modifier). Using ‘no modifier’ is also sometimes
referred as ‘package-private’ or ‘default’ or ‘friendly’ access.

